A: The problem is likely not with the FileWriter, but with the size of the JSON string you are trying to write. The FileWriter will write as many characters as it can, but if the JSON string is too large, it may not be able to write all of it.

For example, if your list have 300 item the length is 78909, this is a very large JSON string. The FileWriter may not be able to write all of it, causing the file to be empty.

You can try to write the JSON string in chunks, rather than all at once. Here is an example of how you can do this:

```java
private void saveTrace() {
    try {
        Log.d(mapsActivity.TAGDEBUG, "Sauvegarde de la trace automatique");
        Log.d(mapsActivity.TAGDEBUG, "Nombre de point compris dans la trace automatique: " + String.valueOf(listBeanTraceUser.size()));
        String sFileNameTrace = "trace_" + currentDate + ".xml";
        File traceFile = new File(root, sFileNameTrace);
        MediaScannerConnection.scanFile(mapsActivity, new String[]{traceFile.getAbsolutePath()}, null, null);
        FileWriter writer = new FileWriter(traceFile);
        BufferedWriter out = new BufferedWriter(writer, 32768);
        String jsonStringTrace = gson.toJson(listBeanTraceUser);
        Log.d(mapsActivity.TAGDEBUG, "lenght jsonStringTrace : " + String.valueOf(jsonStringTrace.length()));

        // Write the JSON string in chunks
        int chunkSize = 1024; // Adjust this value as needed
        for (int i = 0; i < jsonStringTrace.length(); i += chunkSize) {
            out.write(jsonStringTrace.substring(i, Math.min(i + chunkSize, jsonStringTrace.length())));
        }

        out.close();
    } catch (Exception e) {
        Log.d(mapsActivity.TAGDEBUG, "Erreur lors de la Sauvegarde de la trace automatique");
        e.printStackTrace();
    }
}
```

This code will write the JSON string in chunks of 1024 characters each, which should prevent the FileWriter from running out of space. You can adjust the chunk size as needed.
